<TEXT>
the supreme court is concluding its 198889 
term today by issuing its latest word on abortion rights 
the word could come in a momentous ruling or a brief announcement 
that the justices need more time to ponder the fate of legal 
abortions 
the missouri case in which the justices were asked to reverse 
the courts 1973 decision legalizing abortion was the courts most 
closely watched controversy of the decade 
decisions also were pending today in two other cases including 
an important churchstate dispute from pittsburgh and a taxrefund 
case from arkansas and florida 
in each case the justices had to announce a decision or hold it 
over their threemonth summer recess if they chose the latter a 
new round of arguments would be held in the court term that begins 
in october with announcement of a decision likely in 1990 
abortionrights advocates feared the court would order the 
missouri case called webster vs reproductive health services 
reargued next term and simultaneously grant review to up to three 
other abortion disputes pending before the justices 
that likely would be read as a signal that the justices are 
contemplating a major retreat from the 1973 ruling in roe vs wade 
which said women have a constitutional right to abortion 
the court has yet to take action in the other three abortion 
cases which involve state regulations making it harder to get an 
abortion in illinois ohio and minnesota 
roe vs wade itself was argued twice before a decision was 
announced the court hears arguments in about 150 cases each term 
and since 1977 has held over at least one case each year for 
reargument the following term 
the 1973 ruling said a womans decision to have an abortion 
during the first three months of pregnancy must be left to her and 
her doctor it said states may regulate abortions during the second 
trimester only to protect the womans health and may take steps to 
protect fetal life in the third trimester 
state authority to regulate abortions after the first trimester 
was not made absolute however 
in the past decade about 15 million legal abortions have been 
performed each year opponents of roe vs wade wanted to make states 
free to stringently regulate or even outlaw abortion 
antiabortion and prochoice forces had said they did not 
consider it likely that the court would use the missouri case to 
reaffirm roe vs wade 
both sides had believed there could be five votes among the 
courts nine members willing to give states more leeway in 
regulating abortion 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justice byron r white 
dissenters from the 1973 ruling opposed it in each subsequent case 
justices antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy were considered 
willing to reverse or significantly curtail the ruling as well 
justice sandra day oconnor the only woman on the high court 
was seen as possibly providing the key fifth vote 
in two previous abortion rulings she has criticized the 
trimesterbytrimester approach adopted in 1973 and voiced a 
willingness to give states more regulatory power 
