mr bush has got to get up and make the white house the right 
house said the rev joseph lowery president of the southern 
christian leadership conference its not enough to talk that 
talk we need him to walk that walk 
the civil rights act which president johnson signed into law 
july 2 1964 banned segregation in public places and discrimination 
in the workplace 
lowery one of several rights leaders who met with bush on 
friday said recent us supreme court decisions against affirmative 
action programs have left blacks doubting whether the president 
would work to protect progress made under the law 
im going to remain hopeful for the time being lowery said 
mr bush has good instincts he wants to do whats right in this 
regard 
friday bush called on congress to reauthorize the civil rights 
commission which is set to expire nov 30 
attorney general dick thornburgh said last week the 
administration would not push congress to overturn the supreme court 
decisions which make it more difficult to prove discrimination in 
employment 
lowery said civil rights leaders are concerned that bush is 
paying lip service to their cause and added the president is 
going to have to make up his mind by either bolstering black 
membership in the gop or pleasing ultraconservatives 
lowery was joined at kings gravesite by rosa parks whose 
refusal to sit in a segregated section of a montgomery ala bus in 
1955 sparked the civil rights movement 
mrs parks said bushs statements sounded good but we are 
waiting for real real action 
about 200 people gathered for sundays prayer service during 
which lowery blasted supreme court justice sandra day oconnor for 
her position against affirmative action 
glory be to god if it werent for affirmative action shed 
still be in arizona presiding over a microwave lowery said 
adding that the american public should remind sandra who she is 
lowery scolded the crowd for not singing this little light of 
mine with enthusiasm saying that if civil rights leaders had 
sung with that kind of spirit during the movement we would 
still be in slavery 
the crowd responded by singing with threepart harmony 
