<TEXT>
a group of 13 americans leaves for greenland this 
week to try to dig out a squadron of eight world war ii airplanes 
buried in polar ice since 1942 
the us planes two bombers and six fighters are buried 
beneath 260 feet of polar ice the atlantabased greeland expedition 
society wants to dig out all the planes and bring them to the united 
states maybe even repairing one of the fighters on site and flying 
it off the ice 
but expedition members will be happy simply to cut a piece of 
metal from one of the eight aircraft if we could get a control 
wheel out of a b17 it would be ideal said richard taylor an 
architect and pilot who will make the trip 
the eight aircraft are estimated to be worth a total of 5 
million if repaired 
the eight planes have been in greenland since july 15 1942 where 
their crews bellylanded them on the icecap when they ran out of 
fuel the planes had been headed for england but were forced to turn 
back because of bad weather 
on the way back the crews received incorrect weather 
information later there was speculation the information was sent by 
a german uboat 
all 25 crew member were rescued after nine days 
the eight airplanes were covered with snow and essentially 
forgotten until the early 1970s when their story got to pat epps 
an aviation pioneer and owner of epps aviation in atlanta 
several attempts to find the planes were made and last summer 
an expedition located the aircraft by subsurface radar and pushed a 
steam probe down to bump one of the aircraft 
on wednesday the expedition of 13 nine of them pilots leaves 
for the first threeweek trip to greenland they will carry 3 tons 
of food and equipment other supplies have been shipped to iceland 
and will be ferried in as needed 
among the adventurers was norman vaughan 84 of trapper creek 
alaska in 1942 the air force sent thenmaj vaughan a dog musher 
raised in alaska by dog sled to recover a secret bombsight left 
with one of the b17s 
the group will use a 475pound thermal borer to melt a onemeter 
wide hole straight down through the ice to one of the aircraft a 
b17 called big stoop 
once the craft is reached a 2inch disk of metal will be cut 
using a small coring device 
if everything else fails we will have at least one piece of 
tangible proof we have found the aircraft taylor said in a 
weekend interview 
then the group will use electric chain saws to cut a toward the 
plane in a bid to extract if from the ice 
