washington secular symbols 
lower courts across the nation have been confused about just 
where the 1984 ruling drew the line between permissible governmental 
acknowledgment of religious heritages and the unconstitutional 
promotion or advancement of religion 
most lower courts have treated the 1984 decision as a narrow one 
and have disallowed various religious displays deemed too religious 
blackmun acknowledged today that the 1984 ruling is none too 
clear but he said todays ruling may help dispel the confusion 
he said these are the guiding principles the governments use 
of religious symbolism is unconstitutional if it has the effect of 
endorsing religious beliefs and the effect of the governments use 
of religious symoblism depends upon its context 
in pittsburgh from 1981 to 1987 a 9footwide creche depicting 
the birth of jesus christ was displayed inside the county courthouse 
in the city for about six weeks during the christmas season 
a block away an 18foot menorah was displayed each year from 
1982 to 1987 on the front steps of the building that houses city and 
county offices it stood next to a 45foot christmas tree 
a federal judge refused to order the dismantling of the displays 
in late 1987 but the 3rd us circuit court of appeals ruled by a 
21 vote that they were unlawful that ruling prevented the 
displays being shown last christmas season 
the creche is owned by the holy name society a roman catholic 
mens group that arranges for its display the menorah is owned by 
chabad a small jewish sect that loaned the symbol to the city free 
of charge 
the legal controversy began when the american civil liberties 
union asked for removal of the creche and menorah in 1986 the 
request was denied 
the aclu several lawyers who conduct business at the courthouse 
a unitarian minister and a moslem then sued seeking to block the 
displays 
