<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to review a 1984 
federal law requiring that student religious groups be given the 
same access as other extracurricular clubs to public high school 
facilities 
the justices setting the stage for an important ruling on 
churchstate relations said they will decide whether a student 
bible study group must be allowed to meet at an omaha neb high 
school after class hours 
the court will hear an appeal by school officials who say giving 
such access to the club violates the constitutionally required 
separation of church and state 
a decision is expected sometime in 1990 
students at westside high school sought in 1985 to organize a 
christian bible study club officials refused to approve the club 
suggesting the students meet instead at a church next door 
a federal judge ruled in favor of the school officials but the 
8th us circuit court of appeals overturned the decision in 
february saying the club must be allowed to meet on school premises 
the appeals court noted that the high school has let some 30 
other extracurricular groups such as a chess club and a scuba 
diving club meet on school grounds after class hours under a 
faculty members supervision 
congress in 1984 passed the equal access act barring public high 
schools that accept federal aid from discriminating against groups 
based on the religious political philosophical or other content 
of the speech at such meetings 
the law is designed to force schools to give the same privileges 
to religious clubs as other noncurriculumrelated student 
groups 
the supreme court ruled in 1981 that staterun universities 
cannot ban student groups from using campus facilities for religious 
worship and study 
but the justices have not decided whether the same rule should 
apply to high schools 
they examined the issue in 1986 in a pennsylvania case but 
because of a procedural flaw did not answer the question 
at that time four court members said they would let high school 
students conduct such meetings two of those former chief justice 
warren e burger and justice lewis f powell no longer sit on the 
court the two others were nowchief justice william h rehnquist 
and justice byron r white 
justice department lawyers in the former reagan administration 
which also protested the courts ban on organized prayer in public 
schools had pressed for permitting student bible study and worship 
meetings 
the bush administration has not stated its position on the 
nebraska case acted on today 
the 8th circuit court rejected the contention that high school 
students are more impressionable than college students and therefore 
should be given more protection from student religious groups that 
may appear to be sanctioned by school authorities 
we reject this notion because congress considered the 
difference in the maturity level of secondary students and 
university students before passing the equal access act the 
appeals court said we accept congress factfinding 
besides nebraska the 8th circuit court ruling set a binding 
precedent in arkansas iowa minnesota missouri north and south 
dakota 
the case is westside community schools vs mergens 881597 
 
</TEXT>
