<TEXT>
in the hindu kush mountains 
shattered crumbling huts tell tales their inhabitants probably 
never will of the savagery that turned thousands of villages into 
graveyards 
families that tilled the orchards and fields for unknown 
generations have disappeared the silence is broken by an occasional 
burst of gunfire or a military convoy roaring through the valleys 
where shattered villages cling to the 15000foot mountains like an 
image of armageddon 
what happened to villages like lalma babagilala babamardan and 
babashangrul will not be known until the war between the government 
and moslem guerrillas ends and accounts can be pieced together from 
villagers who escaped 
after a decade of war the barbarity has become widely known but 
in the hindu kush mountains along the river valleys and across the 
plains where the armies of alexander the great and genghis khan once 
marched the scenes of devastation go beyond what was previously 
known about the conflict 
international relief workers fear they are only beginning to 
learn of the destruction wrought on the rebelcontrolled countryside 
there are black holes places no one has been for years and 
probably wont get to until the war is over but if what we know now 
is a barometer of the level of destruction this war has been almost 
genocidal said one international aid worker speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
according to asif zahir minister of planning and reconstruction 
at least half the countrys 35500 villages have been bombed 
shelled and rocketed into oblivion fields orchards and irrigation 
canals vital to this agriculturally dependent society are in ruins 
once peace is restored relief workers say it will take years 
and billions of dollars to bring what was already one of the worlds 
poorest countries back to the point it was in april 1978 when 
marxists seized power and civil war broke out 
government and military officials say the devastation occurred 
progressively over 11 years of fighting as the guerrillas occupied 
the villages and the afghan army and soviet troops sent in to help 
battled to uproot them 
across afghanistan in villages and towns of the western 
southern and eastern provinces the conflict has destroyed all 
semblance of civilized living entire districts lie in rubble 
schools medical facilities and public utilities have disappeared 
soldiers of the sovietbacked kabul government say much of the 
destruction occurred in the final weeks before feb 15 when the 
kremlin withdrew the last of its troops from afghanistan 
fearing attacks on retreating convoys by guerrillas hiding in the 
villages the soviets ordered bombing raids and artillery barrages 
on the villages and other suspected guerrilla hideouts along the 
departure routes 
those that were lucky got out and those that couldnt probably 
died brig gen mohammad shafi who commands the second infantry 
division said in a matteroffact tone 
after the red army was gone the usbacked guerrillas slipped 
back to their posts the afghan army mounted another offensive and 
forced the rebels to retreat into the snowcovered mountains a 
second time 
the enemy used to be here we had to come and punish them and 
destroy their hideouts said shafi pointing to the ruins around 
haijan scene of some of the fiercest battles since the soviet 
pullout 
along the sinuous salang highway which climbs through the hindu 
kush and winds north toward the soviet union soldiers now stand 
guard at military outposts interspersed with hundreds of burned out 
tanks and armored personnel carriers 
but the wreckage littering the road and the hulks of tanks and 
trucks blasted into the icy rushing water of the salang river are 
little compared to the destruction that lies above the road 
relief workers estimate it will take at least 1 billion to start 
rebuilding and billions of dollars more for several years 
zahir the reconstruction minister predicts most reconstruction 
could be completed within five years but he added that some things 
can never be replaced 
you cant rebuild a society with mere money there are many 
values that have been destroyed by this war he said 
you can always rebuild a road or a well of a piece of land but 
millions of people some of the brightest minds in afghanistan have 
left how do you bring them back more than a million afghans have 
died we cannot revive them 
