<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed the government 
to enforce antidumping regulations in a way foreign companies and 
importers of foreign goods say improperly impedes international 
trade 
the court without comment rejected a canadian steel producers 
appeal which was supported by an american exportimport association 
and an international consumers group 
algoma steel corp ltd of canada challenged a decision by the 
international trade commission a us agency responsible for 
enforcing some antidumping rules 
the commission said that canadian steel tubing was being dumped 
sold at below fair market value in the united states the 
commission said such sales were injuring or threatening injury to 
us industry 
the finding permits imposition of antidumping duties to penalize 
foreign companies and importers of the steel products 
the commerce department which shares responsibility for 
enforcing antidumping rules said some of algoma steels exports to 
the united states were sold above fair market value 
commerce officials said that over one sixmonth period more than 
half of algoma steels exports were sold above fair market value 
algoma steel said that fact in effect was ignored when the 
international trade commission determined dumped goods were causing 
injury to us industry 
the canadian company said any fairly traded products should be 
excluded from the commissions assessment 
but a federal appeals court here upheld the commissions finding 
in january ruling the commission did not act arbitrarily or 
capriciously when it included the fairly trade goods in its 
calculations 
many such fairly traded sales might be the best evidence 
possible that the lessthanfairvalue sales had served their 
purpose and the united states competitor was in full retreat the 
appeals court said it is therefore not at all obvious that the 
morethanfairvalue sales are automatically legally irrelevant 
algoma steels appeal was supported by the american association 
of exporters and importers representing 1200 us companies 
involved in international trade 
the inclusion of fairly traded imports to decide injury in a 
dumping case blurs the distinction between fair trade and unfair 
trade thereby penalizing honest us importers who follow 
internationally acceptable practices the association said 
also backing the appeal was consumers for world trade which said 
us trade law was being misused to erect protectionist barriers 
the bush administration urged the justices to reject the appeal 
the case is algoma steel vs us 881781 
</TEXT>
