<TEXT>
eight southern pilots begin a fourday flight to 
greenland on wednesday for an expedition aimed at reaching one of 
eight aircraft buried deep in the icecap since they crashlanded 
during world war ii 
the two b17 bombers and six p38 lightning fighters are buried 
under 265 feet of ice and snow that has accumulated since bad 
weather and low fuel forced them to abort a flight to england in 
1942 
the greenland expedition society headed by atlanta architect 
richard taylor and pat epps an aviation pioneer and owner of epps 
aviation located the planes with subsurface radar and magnetometers 
last summer 
this year they want a piece of one aircraft a b17 named big 
stoop in part to help persuade investors to finance an effort to 
bring the planes back to the united states next year 
they are estimated to be worth 5 million if repaired 
if we could get a control wheel out of a b17 it would be 
ideal taylor said but even just a piece of metal cut out of its 
skin would be tangible proof we found the aircraft 
the team plans to bore a 2inch hole to the plane with a steam 
borer and cut out a piece of metal with a coring device then bore a 
wider shaft so they can reach the plane and try to get inside 
their 3 tons of equipment ing above the clouds are insulated 
from the sights sounds and smells of rural america it has not 
always been so come along on a nostalgic trip with the jones 
family whose expeditions in the early and middle 1920s from tulsa 
okla to grandmothers house in eau claire wis were as removed 
from the present day as that day was removed from the pony express 
and covered wagons 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the missing keys to the new 1925 paige sedan not only caused an 
uproar in the jones family but the whole payroll of the commercial 
hotel of nebraska city was engaged in a futile search 
my fathers famous temper climbed through the night and was not 
improved the next morning when the local locksmith confessed he was 
baffled by the trick lock on the gearshift after considerable 
shouting into feeble long distance lines an expert was summoned 
from omaha 
dick my big brother who had driven the paige into town was the 
obvious object of suspicion and outrage his usual ploy you had 
it last pointing at me wouldnt work for i was too young to 
drive the expert came installed a new lock relieved my father of 
150 and the family drove out of town a day late in a cloud of 
steam 
at dusk two days later dick and i were walking across a bridge 
at zumbrota minn dick paused and drew out of his pocket the 
original paige keys 
whered you find them 
the darned things slipped down a hole in the lining of my 
pants he said 
the keys arced prettily into the murky waters of the zumbro 
river as far as i know they are still there 
the expeditions of the jones family in the early and middle 1920s 
from tulsa okla to my grandmothers house at eau claire wis 
were as removed from the present day as that day was removed from 
the pony express and covered wagons 
prudence dictated that we go by rail but all except dad would 
spend the summer and grandmothers willis knight wouldnt be large 
enough so starting in 1921 we made touring history and tested the 
familys mutual toleration severely 
in the midwest there was no highway system federal or state 
some enthusiast had blazed what was called the omahatulsa trail 
and ots splashed crudely in green paint appeared occasionally on 
telephone poles between towns but mostly you picked your way from 
village to village by asking farmers occasionally you used the 
blue book 
a blue book in good condition should be worth its weight in 
platinum now for practically all motorists dropped them in the 
ashcans when numbered highways came as a bit of americana of the 
times they were marvelous example 
bugville mile 0 proceed north on main from elm 43 miles to 
large white house right side with red barn left to mile 91 at 
cherry creek bridge right across railroad 
the trouble with the blue book was that people repainted houses 
barns burned and the county often put in a better road a mile east 
but blue book users saw so much more because they paid attention 
city people tulsa in 1920 with pop 72000 was a city lived in 
the ambiance of the 20th century but you didnt get far out of town 
before you were back in the 19th after the sun went down the 
country grew dark except for the firefly flickers of coaloil wicks 
motels had not been invented so daring motorists stayed with the 
railroadriding drummers in town hotels generally named after the 
proprietor with the word house tacked on the end 
indoor plumbing had arrived generally one bathroom to a floor 
for the benefit of those just dropping in to lunch there was often a 
tin basin on the back stoop and you threw the soapy water on the 
grass 
fortunately i was born into the postbedbug era for by the 
early 20s country hotel sheets were changed every day but neither 
were accommodations homogenized the modern phenomenon of climatized 
rooms as alike as peas from coast to coast was far in the future 
upscale county seat hotels had menus but most others served 
family style at 6 am the board groaned with calories and 
cholesterol stewed prunes oatmeal thick cream fried eggs ham 
bacon corn fritters waffles and at 630 most of the spearing 
reaching toothpicksucking mob would dash off with their battered 
sample cases for the early trains 
there was still much individuality in hotel design and decor at 
the leading hostelry in red wing minn one entered the bedroom 
through the bathroom 
the principal hotel in atlantic iowa had once been a 
chiropractic college a fullsize skeleton lurked around the corner 
as you came upstairs no doubt filling late arrivals with amusement 
when we came exhausted and on a superheated evening to sabetha 
kan we were directed to what was described as the best hotel on 
the grand island we didnt know that the grand island railroad 
was only 100 miles long and passed through practically nothing 
that night we three children lay in our underwear crosswise on 
the bed gasping for breath there was a movie going on beneath the 
thin floor and you could sort of follow the plot with the help of 
the girl at the piano 
when she played rachmaninoffs prelude you knew the rustlers were 
sneaking up on the corral when she played the finale of william 
tells overture you could tell the posse was in full cry heavy 
banging on the bass keys told you the gun battle was joined and 
when she swung softly into hearts and flowers it said that 
wedding bells were not far off and the movie would soon be over 
getting up to grandmas wouldnt have been as exciting if only 
the parents and children had been traveling but since we were 
making a summer of it the car also contained the cat our black 
belgian shepherd blig and tony the african gray parrot 
the cat which loved comfort more than it loved the family had 
to be recaught every morning for it remembered the day before 
until the wheels moved we would stuff it in a covered basket 
the survival power of tony was amazing for dad was a furious 
driver and the car was in the air most of the time tony braced 
himself with one foot on the perch and the other clinging to the 
wire of the cage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

