<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday accepted its 
firstever righttodie case agreeing to decide whether a 
missouri couple can remove their braindamaged daughter from a 
lifesupport system 
nancy cruzan 31 has been in what doctors describe as a 
persistent vegetative condition since a january 1983 car crash 
her parents joe and joyce cruzan want to remove the feeding 
tube surgically planted in her stomach without it doctors said she 
would die of starvation or dehydration with it they said she may 
live for 30 years or more 
the court said it would review a 43 ruling of the missouri 
supreme court that forbid doctors from removing the tube a decision 
is expected next year 
we are pretty elated around here her father said in a 
telephone interview from carterville mo after learning the case 
will be heard by the nations highest court we are trying to do 
what nancy would want us to do 
ms cruzan is able to breathe on her own and has periods of 
wakefulness in which her eyes move randomly in all directions 
doctors say she is incapable of reacting or relating to her 
environment and can experience no thoughts or emotions 
her hands and feet have constricted bent into claw shapes 
because of the brain damage 
her parents said their daughter at one time had said she would 
not want to be kept alive in such a condition 
but the missouri supreme court said we find no principled 
legal basis which permits the coguardians in this case to choose 
the death of their ward the states interest is in the preservation 
of life not only nancys life but also the lives of persons 
similarly situated yet without the support of a loving family 
it added we choose to err on the side of life respecting the 
rights of incompetent persons who may wish to live despite a 
severely diminished quality of life 
the state supreme court overturned a judges ruling that would 
have allowed the cruzans to order the feeding tube removed 
the missouri legislature has enacted a law a socalled living 
will statute that permits the withdrawal of artificial 
lifesupport systems from hopelessly ill and injured patients but 
the law specifically forbids withholding food and water from them 
the american medical association and other organizations joined 
the cruzans in urging the supreme court to overturn the state court 
ruling 
the medical groups said us hospitals care for from 5000 to 
10000 people in a persistent vegetative state 
the organizations said many state legislatures and a handful of 
state appeals courts have approved the withdrawal of lifesupport 
systems in such cases 
the supreme court has declined in the past to study the 
righttodie issue 
missouri attorney general william webster whose office argued 
against removing the feeding tube said he is glad the court decided 
to hear the case 
there are families all across the country that deserve a 
definite statement from the supreme court on the issue webster 
said there is a split among the lower courts on this issue and it 
is appropriate that the highest court in the land consider the 
issue 
in the most publicized case to reach them the justices let stand 
a 1976 new jersey supreme court ruling that allowed the removal of a 
respirator helping karen ann quinlan breathe 
ms quinlan also in an irreversible vegetative state continued 
to be fed through a tube and lived an additional nine years 
the case is cruzan vs missouri department of health 881503 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

