<TEXT>
producers of rabbiteye blueberries are urged to 
be on the lookout for an newly discovered insect friend a bee with 
a long tongue 
the agriculture department said monday that honey bees cant 
pollinate rabbiteye blueberries because their tongues are too short 
but the new bees tongue is longer and can reach into the 
blueberrys flower for nectar 
as it probes the flower with its long tongue the bee also buzzes 
it to loosen a cloud of pollen said jerry a payne an entomologist 
with the departments agricultural research service 
when the bee moves on it carries pollen from one blueberry 
flower to another achieving pollination payne who works at the 
agencys southeastern fruit and tree nut research laboratory byron 
ga said in a report issued here that poor crops of rabbiteye 
blueberries often result from poor cross pollination 
the groundnesting bee habropoda loboriosa was found during a 
threeyear study with auburn university in alabama the bee is 
prevalent in the southeastern united states where rabbiteye 
blueberries are grown on approximately 5000 acres 
payne said the bee which has been named the southeastern 
blueberry bee is larger than a honey bee but smaller than a bumble 
bee the female has a black face minus a creamcolored dot that 
distinguishes the male only the female gathers pollen 
depending on the season consumers pay from 2 to 5 a pint for 
rabbiteye blueberries 
we dont know much about the bees nesting habits payne 
said therefore we dont have any way yet to reintroduce it if 
nests are destroyed so we advice growers not to use insecticides 
when blueberries bloom 
</TEXT>
