<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday agreed to use a 
race discrimination case from north carolina to explore the right to 
a jury trial by those filing civil lawsuits 
the court said it will hear during its next term beginning in 
october an appeal by a machinist who said he was fired because he 
is black a ruling in the case is likely in 1990 
the machinist john s lytle had worked for more than two years 
at the household manufacturing inc plant in arden nc he was 
fired after failing to show up for work on aug 12 1983 
he said he was ill and wanted the day off to see a doctor lytle 
said he planned to work on aug 13 a saturday to make up the 
time but was prevented from telling his supervisor of his plan 
because the supervisor was angry with him over another incident 
lytle then filed a complaint with the federal equal employment 
opportunity commission charging his employer with racial bias in 
the firing 
he also said the company in retaliation for his eeoc complaint 
refused to provide him with a letter of recommendation to help him 
get another job 
lytle filed a federal suit under a centuryold civil rights law 
first used to protect freed slaves 
that same law was the center of a heated controversy last month 
when the supreme court reaffirmed the act can be used to charge 
private employers with bias in that same ruling the justices 
limited the law by ruling that the statute cannot be invoked to 
charge onthejob racial harassment 
the case acted on monday involves a different application of the 
law 
lytle was denied a jury trial by a federal judge who in 1986 
ruled that the 19th century law did not offer him a remedy the 
judge then examined lytles complaint under the civil rights act of 
1964 which also forbids onthejob racial discrimination 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals ruled in 1987 that the 
judge was apparently erroneous in barring lytles complaint 
based on the older law 
but the appeals court refused to reinstate lytles suit 
the appeals court said the suit may not be revived because the 
federal judge examined lytles complaint under the 1964 statute and 
ruled there was insufficient evidence to support his bias claim 
the appeals court said the handling of the employment 
discrimination charge under the 19th century law and under the 1964 
act are identical 
where the elements of the two causes of action are the same 
the findings by the trial judge in one preclude the trial of the 
other the appeals court said 
the case is lytle vs household manufacturing 88334 
