<TEXT>
lech walesas wife and a son represented him 
monday night at a formal dinner preceding the award of the first 
philadelphia liberty medal to the polish solidarity leader 
danuta walesa and one of her sons yaroslaw 15 will stand in 
for walesa at the citys traditional fourth of july ceremony 
tuesday they are to be presented with the medal and the 100000 
cash award that accompanies it 
after monday nights dinner mrs walesa was introduced to the 
crowd of about 500 people by former us sen edmund muskie 
dmaine who was secretary of state under president carter 
mrs walesa received a standing ovation then thanked her 
admirers in halting polish which was translated into english 
tuesdays ceremonies will cap the fourday freedom festival 
which included a hotair balloon race parade food festival 
concerts and several fireworks shows 
walesa who won the nobel peace prize in 1983 had said he could 
not attend the ceremonies because of the effort to install a new 
government in poland following the communist countrys first largely 
democratic elections in more than four decades 
philadelphia civic leaders intended the award to focus national 
attention on philadelphia on independence day 
more than 80 nominations were reviewed by an international 
selection committee the award is meant for an individual or 
organization that has demonstrated leadership and vision in the 
pursuit of liberty of conscience or freedom from oppression 
ignorance or deprivation 
the committee said walesa was chosen not only because of his 
courage over many years but also because of his recent 
accomplishments in poland expanding the prospects of political and 
economic liberty 
solidarity was born in the occupation strike at the lenin 
shipyard in gdansk in august 1980 walesa a shipyard electrician 
from the port city led the strike and emerged a folk hero the 
union was recognized as the soviet blocs only legally independent 
union but polish officials later suppressed solidarity activities 
interned walesa and banned the union 
in january 1989 the government decided solidarity could be 
formally registered again as an independent trade union 
walesa 46 and his wife have eight children 
