<TEXT>
with all flags flying fireworks bursting in 
air congress in recess and president bush in kennebunkport theres 
a holiday pause in the legislative race toward a constitutional ban 
on flag burning 
but not in the patriotic speechmaking 
house speaker thomas s foley wants calm careful deliberations 
in place of the emotional rush to amend the constitution and 
overrule the supreme court 
the political tide is not running that way 
theres an amendment ready to go bush went to the flagraising 
iwo jima monument overlooking washington on friday to urge swift 
congressional approval of a simple direct and to the point 
amendment 
it declares 
the congress and the states shall have power to prohibit the 
physical desecration of the flag of the united states 
at a hastily arranged rally the president said for the sake of 
the fallen for the men behind the guns for every american we will 
defend this flag 
the defense is symbolic theres no sign that the flag is in 
danger of wholesale desecration the court license notwithstanding 
while in recess house members who joined an allnight flagathon 
can attest to their patriotism by shipping home television tapes of 
the speeches they made during a session that kept going until nearly 
9 am thursday there was nobody on the floor to listen but the 
tapes wont show that 
before recessing for independence day the senate and house both 
adopted resolutions assailing the supreme courts june 21 decision 
that burning an american flag is a permissible expression of protest 
under the first amendment 
the issue is easy and automatic the agenda in congress is filled 
with close questions and hard choices but not this one it is black 
and white or red white and blue 
most everybody signed on three senators and five house members 
voted against the resolutions saying that the right to dissent was 
too precious for tampering even on flag desecration which they all 
denounced 
one of them sen gordon humphrey of new hampshire offered a 
conservatives common sense but was drowned out by the chorus of 
flag speeches 
no one likes desecration but this just seems to me an exercise 
in silliness and even a little bit of hypocrisy if i may say so 
humphrey told the senate 
in the house foley said congress should act carefully on the 
issue with hearings on the best way to protect the flag 
there does seem to be time for that but it doesnt fit the 
political mood 
behind it all lies a question the supreme court doesnt answer 
why the justices chose to deal with the flag case in the first 
place it was not an urgent issue indeed hardly a visible one 
until the court ruled even though 48 states and the federal 
government had flag desecration laws it involved a flag burning 
conviction that already had been overturned by a texas appeals court 
which got no national attention 
and there are other ways to punish people who burn flags in 
public places the court said it wasnt suggesting a flag burner 
couldnt be prosecuted for stealing the flag involved was snatched 
from in front of a dallas texas bank or for trespassing 
disorderly conduct or arson 
but the court has said all it will say and the next move is up 
to congress it will reconvene on july 11 the house offering its 
regular pledge of allegiance to the flag at the start of its 
session during the flag outcry more than one member noted that 
practice no member noted its origin 
the house pledge is hardly a tradition it began last sept 13 
when bush was making the pledge of allegiance into a campaign issue 
against gov michael dukakis who once vetoed a bill to require it 
in massachusetts classrooms 
until that happened the house said the pledge once a year on 
flag day june 14 
