<TEXT>
as a columnist for the new york times and a 
pulitzer prizewinning author russell baker has settled into a 
comfortable way of life 
no more cruising the streets of baltimore in search of crime 
stories no coronations to cover no waiting in the halls of 
congress for politicians to lie to him 
he and his wife mimi have a home of their own now in leesburg 
va just what his mother dreamed of when she raised him during the 
great depression baker has stuck with journalism for more than 40 
years always remembering his mothers advice to never be a quitter 
to make something of himself 
but he still has some unfinished business growing up the 
bestselling account of his childhood ended in the late 1940s with 
his marraige and his early days with the baltimore sun 
in a summer of sequels on the big screen baker continues his 
life story with the good times 1995 morrow 
this book was inevitable after growing up he said i was 
amazed at the mail i had received and still receive so many people 
led the same life 
memoirs are by famous men and cast light on great events these 
are more letters to my family 
baker was just another rewrite man and police reporter at the 
sun horrified at the hopeless poverty he had witnessed in the slums 
of baltimore when buck dorsey the managing editor phoned and 
invited him to lunch at the posh chesapeake restaurant 
after several martinis dorsey stunned his young employee by 
offering the assignment of london bureau chief 
i really dont know why he did it baker said ive got 
some guesses just guesses buck was a gambling man all real 
baltimoreans are gamblers he picked me out as somebody to bet on 
he was sort of running me testing his eye 
the london experience changed my life it gave me an education 
humanized me exposed me to theater ballet and music a few weeks 
earlier i had been writing stories about purse snatching now im 
covering winston churchill and anthony eden being briefed by john 
foster dulles 
the good times is a book of turning points a chronicle of 
unexpected breaks baker puts himself back in the mind of the 
ordinary man astonished at his own good fortune 
i wanted to get inside the skin of how events are happening at 
the time if i wrote it as an essay now as an old granddad looking 
back it wouldnt be the same i wanted to convey the sense of what 
was going on as a youngster 
i was like somebody thrown into swirling water i was just 
swimming i didnt have any sense of going any place i was 
learning and it was fascinating 
after returning to the united states in 1954 baker was hired by 
the new york times and served as a correspondent in washington 
unlike his colleagues however he didnt concern himself with 
the differences between democrats and republicans instead he 
studied personalities and was fascinated by lyndon johnson then the 
senates powerful majority leader 
he was a million things it was like peeling an onion he could 
tell you a story and reduce himself to tears then he could turn on 
you with a snarl he was one of the great mysteries baker said 
of all the politicians i covered he was the one character that 
would have interested shakespeare sometimes hes like king lear 
then hes like macbeth then hes a buffoon like falstaff 
baker also found himself oddly attracted to richard nixon then 
vice president under president eisenhower like baker the gloomy 
awkward nixon grew up poor and struggled to advance himself 
john f kennedy was a rich mans son he had been a hero in 
world war ii everything had come easy to him i could identify with 
nixon he had suffered and was terribly scarred by the experience i 
could feel for him i could sympathize for him but it was almost 
impossible to like him baker said 
but presidents and congressmen never interested baker the way 
writers did for a man whose heroes included ernest hemingway and 
eb white the intrigues of washington never entirely consumed him 
by 1962 he knew his days as a reporter were numbered that a 
leisurely lunch meant more to him than any senate subcommittee when 
the sun asked him to write for their editorial page the times 
topped it giving baker the observer column he still has today 
when i went to london for the sun baker recalled once a 
week there was a column we had called from a window in fleet 
street the home of newspapers in london 
that was my first experience at writing a column i discovered 
i liked it it was a wonderful release from the rigors of objective 
reporting i could deal with character and color 
baker has no plans for a russell baker iii or sequel to his 
lifes story 
im just a columnist now nothing happens to me anymore 
baker said nothing ever happens to a columnist they just 
ossify 
</TEXT>
